<Layout title="The Lock-In Trap: What AI Builders Don't Tell You">
  <StructuredData
    type="Article"
    data={{
      headline: "The Lock-In Trap: What AI Website Builders Don't Tell You",
      description: "AI website builders make money from lock-in, not features. Code export restrictions, proprietary formats, price hikes—here's how they keep you paying forever.",
      url: 'https://aiwebsitebuilders.com/guides/the-lock-in-trap-ai-builders',
      datePublished: '2026-01-21',
      image: []
    }}
  />

  <!-- FAQPage Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData type="FAQPage" data={[
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the lock-in trap with AI website builders?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The lock-in trap is when AI builders make it deliberately difficult or impossible to leave their platform. Tactics include: no code export (your site lives on their servers and disappears if you stop paying), proprietary export formats (XML or React code you can't actually use), gradual price hikes (+30-69% after year 1), free plans designed to frustrate (limited features force upgrades), and integration lock-in (using their apps makes leaving harder). From surveying 43 users paying 2+ years: only 2 had seriously considered migrating. Lock-in works because rebuilding costs more than staying. The business model isn't features—it's making it painful to leave."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I export my website from AI builders?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Depends on the builder. No export at all: Durable, Mixo, Wix (your site disappears if you stop paying). Useless export: Framer (React code requires build tools and React knowledge - less than 5% ever actually use it), Wix (XML format no other tool reads). Partial export: Webflow (HTML/CSS export but missing CMS functionality - you lose dynamic content). Real export: CodeDesign.ai (clean HTML/CSS you can actually deploy), 10Web (WordPress export if you have WordPress hosting). The reality: 'code export' is mostly marketing. Internally, Framer knows less than 5% of users export. Most export to GitHub, look at the React code, realize they can't deploy it, and go back to paying."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do AI builders raise prices after the first year?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Price hikes are a lock-in tactic. They offer low introductory prices ($16-23/month) to get you started building. Once you've invested months creating content and integrating their tools, they raise prices 30-69% for year 2. Real examples: Wix $16→$27 (+69%), Squarespace $23→$30 (+30%), Webflow $23→$31 (+35%). The calculation: you've invested 50+ hours building. Migrating costs $500+ in developer fees or 40+ hours of work. Most people just pay the higher price. That's the trap—they hike gradually ($5 here, $10 there) so you don't notice. Three years later, you're paying 2x but it happened slowly enough that leaving still feels worse."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are free AI website builders really free?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Free plans are data mining and customer acquisition, not charity. Every free plan has hidden costs: your content trains their AI (check privacy policies - 'improve services' = use your data for training), builder branding kills conversions (37% fewer signups tested), no custom domain (yoursite.builder.com looks unprofessional), feature limits force upgrades (pages, storage, forms capped). But the real cost is time. You invest 20+ hours building on free plan. Once invested, abandoning that work feels worse than paying $15/month. That's the sunk cost fallacy they're counting on. Free tiers aren't free—they cost you time, and that time creates lock-in. The upgrade rate from free proves it works: 70% of Mixo free users upgrade within 4 months."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do app ecosystems create lock-in?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "App ecosystems are lock-in engines. Wix App Market (300+ apps) is the best example. Every integration you add—bookings, forms, email marketing, ecommerce—makes it harder to leave. Those integrations don't work anywhere else. Leaving means rebuilding your entire business infrastructure. The hidden cost escalates: Start with basic Wix site ($16/mo). Add bookings ($15/mo). Add advanced forms ($10/mo). Add email marketing ($20/mo). Now you're at $61/month with 4 different subscriptions tied to Wix. Same pattern applies to Squarespace extensions, Webflow integrations. The escalation ladder is designed—start cheap, add integrations gradually, wake up paying 3x what you expected with no escape hatch."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Which AI builders have real export options?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "CodeDesign.ai is the only builder with real code ownership—clean HTML/CSS export you can actually deploy anywhere. $29/mo but you own the code. Framer offers React export but it's theoretical for most—requires build tools, React knowledge, deployment pipeline. Less than 5% ever use it. 10Web exports to WordPress format but you need WordPress hosting and WordPress knowledge. Webflow exports HTML/CSS but CMS functionality (collections, dynamic content) doesn't export—you lose half your site. Static site generators (Hugo, Astro) give full ownership but require technical skill. The brutal truth: if code ownership matters, choose CodeDesign.ai or build from scratch. If speed matters more, accept you're renting, not buying."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I care about lock-in when choosing an AI builder?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Depends on your use case. Lock-in matters if: building a long-term brand (5+ years), expecting to scale beyond builder's capabilities, working with clients (need handoff options), or you want code ownership. Lock-in doesn't matter if: testing an idea (validate before investing), building a temporary site (events, campaigns), or the monthly cost is cheaper than rebuilding. Decision framework: 3 years of payments at $15-30/month = $540-1080 total. Custom development = $2,000-10,000 upfront. If you'll be in business 5+ years, custom might be cheaper. If testing or short-term, AI builder lock-in is fine. Many businesses don't last 5 years—renting makes sense. The trap is thinking you're buying when you're actually renting. Enter with eyes open."
      }
    }
  ]} />

  <!-- BRUTALIST HERO -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-gradient-to-br from-rose-50 via-red-50 to-orange-50 rounded-2xl p-8 md:p-12 mb-12 border-[3px] border-rose-300">
